Content:
AEO Conf Recordings: aeoconf.com
Graphite + AirOps Rewriting AEO Rules Keynote

Key Takeaways
* Mobile accounts for 75-86% of AI usage and is excluded from most published data, making the real number 4-5x larger than what is commonly cited.
* AI is already over half the size of search worldwide, up 300% year over year. ChatGPT owns 86% of the AI market.
* The pie is getting bigger, not redistributing. Search has not declined. The combined channel is up 16% in the US and 26% worldwide.

Long Tail Prompt Mismatch
* Average Google search is 3.5 words. Over 60% of ChatGPT prompts are 10+ words. Marketers are still tracking ~7-word prompts in AEO tools, measuring the head of a channel that is almost entirely tail.
* The long tail of AI prompts has almost no content competing for it.

Prompt Discovery Gap
* ChatGPT does not share prompt data. The only way to find out what people are actually asking is to look where they already ask: sales calls, support tickets, Reddit threads.
* Most marketing teams have no strategy built around this despite it being the majority of AI activity.

Distributed Citations and Consensus Building
* 95% of cited domains fall outside the top ten. Reddit is number one at 2.36% of all citations.
* AI synthesizes consensus. Being mentioned across many sources matters more than ranking first in one. Volume and distribution beat depth in a single channel.

Content Refresh Is the Most Ignored Growth Lever
* Stale content gets cited significantly less than fresh content. For teams with existing content libraries, refreshing pages is likely higher ROI than creating new ones.
* For technical content, refresh quality depends on accuracy: correct model names, valid code samples, and current documentation references. This can be built as a recurring automated workflow.

Sales Call Signals & Opportunities
* Customer questions in sales calls, support tickets, and call recordings contain the long-tail prompts AI is being asked.
* Frontier questions, triggered by new launches or competitor moves, often have zero content on the web. Being first to answer them is a structural advantage that most teams are not pursuing.

