Evaluation & Critiques Of AI Growth Study
I posted a study last week about the growth of AI and received questions about the accuracy of ChatGPT's traffic numbers. I want to describe my methodology and the data sources of this study.

How I Calculated ChatGPT Is 20% Of Search Related Prompts
1. I used data from Similarweb.
2. Search Engines: Sum the website visits of the top 6 search engines (Google, Yahoo, Bing, DuckDuckGo, Baidu, Yandex)
3. AI: Sum website visits and mobile app sessions for the top 5 LLMs (ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity, Claude, Grok).
4. Adjust AI sessions when comparing to search using "Asking" prompts definition from ChatGPT.

You can review the raw data here with source links to each report on Similarweb.
https://lnkd.in/dViVbBgZ

Why Does Ethan's Study Disagree With Rand's Study?
It does not. We are looking at different views of the data.
1. He looked at desktop web visits. My study looked at desktop web, mobile web, and mobile native apps.
2. He looked at 41 total companies, I looked at 11. He included other surfaces for search, like Instagram, Amazon, and YouTube. I only looked at traditional search engines and not vertical search engines.
3. He looked at US, I looked at worldwide.

Rand posted a critique of my study on Friday, specifically regarding the traffic data for ChatGPT. However, he used US MAUs rather than worldwide visits, which he later corrected. Using data from Similarweb, we still see that 83% of ChatGPT sessions are on mobile apps, and 20% of search-related traffic comes from ChatGPT when looking at worldwide visits (adjusted for asking prompts). I include links to the data sources above to validate these two data points.

I also want to highlight that Simon Kemp and DataReportal's numbers are also accurate, and they do not have a data error. They are consistent with both my numbers and Similarweb's numbers. This was a mistake on Rand’s part confusing worldwide MAUs and US MAUs and not a data error, which he later corrected.

Google Mobile App
A criticism that I think is fair is that I did not fully consider Google’s mobile app usage. It’s unclear to me whether this changes my numbers or not. I am investigating this and will update my numbers if I indeed missed this.

Different Views Of The Data
I also posted many different views of the data. Some people saw only one of my posts and argued that it did not give full context (e.g. the 56% AI number is misleading because it does not adjust for asking prompts). However, I tried to show many different views of the data in my study to give a more complete picture (e.g. I did explain asking vs. non-asking prompts and included prompts adjusted for asking in a separate post).

Peer Review
It’s helpful for people to critique research, especially when two numbers don’t agree. I welcome and encourage criticism of my studies.

