Search & AI Are Not Zero-Sum, The Pie Is Getting Bigger
This is another theme related to my most recent study on the growth of AI.
https://lnkd.in/dCVNv4nw

The Myth Of The Converging Lines Of Google & ChatGPT
The prevailing narrative is that the rapid growth of AI is causing a rapid decrease in search. This is based on the premise that search and AI are "zero-sum."

Zero-Sum Bias - If AI is now 56% the size of search, then search must have decreased proportionally to this. Some markets are zero-sum, and others are not.

“The Web Is Dead” Circa 2010
In 2008, Apple introduced the ability to create mobile apps. Many people claimed that mobile apps would soon overtake the web and that the web would eventually die as a result.

Mobile apps did eventually reach the potential that was claimed. But the web never died, the pie just got much bigger.

The Truth - Search & AI Are Not Zero-Sum, The Pie Is Getting Bigger
1. Search is not declining.
2. AI is now 56% the size of search.
3. There are new user intents in AI. 13.8% of prompts are expressing, 34.6% are doing.
4. If we adjust traffic numbers to consider only Asking prompts (search-related), the pie is still getting much bigger. Total usage of search combining search engines and search on LLMs has increased by 26% worldwide and by 16% in the US, comparing 2025 with 2024.
